(metadata 
    
    (info
        {
        (description "Lifeline is a territorial strategy game for two players. It was invented by Michael Amundsen and Luis Bolanos Mures in February 2022, and is inspired by Go and Kanare Kato's Meridians.")
        (rules "Lifeline is a territorial strategy game for two players that is played on the cells of a hexhex board (or, equivalently, on the points of a hexagonally shaped isometric grid).
            Size 6 is the smallest recommended size.
            
            Definitions:
            A group is a stone along with all other stones one could reach from it through a series of steps between adjacent stones of the same color.
            Two distinct groups are said to be allies if they are of the same color.
            Two groups are said to reach each other if they are adjacent to the same contiguous region of empty points. 
            
            Setup:
            Starting with Black, the players take turns placing stones of their own color on empty points, one stone per turn. 
            This initial phase ends when each player has two stones on the board. 
            Neither stone may be adjacent to the other of its color.
            
            Play:
            Each turn, you place a stone of your color on an empty point.
            After your placement, remove all enemy groups that do not reach an ally group.
            At the end of your turn, each of your groups must reach an ally group.
            The last player to make a placement wins.
            
            Optional meta-rules (for balance):
            The pie rule:
            When playing with the pie rule, White has the option to swap sides after Black's first move. If White chooses to swap, they become Black, and the player who started out as Black plays as White from the immediately next turn onwards.
            
            12* protocol:
            When playing with the 12* protocol, players make two placements each turn, except for Blacks very first turn. The wincondition does not discriminate between the first and second placement in a turn, so even if you were able to make your first placement, you lose if you are unable to complete your turn by making the second placement.
            
            Komi:
            When playing with komi, a whole number of points is given to White as compensation for going second. 
            In stead of making a normal placement, white has the option to spend one point of komi.
            This has no other effect than reducing the number of points they have available to spend, but, crucially, it technically counts as a placement (a null-placement), so White can win by being the last player to spend a point of Komi.
            In this implementation, komi is spent by clicking the shield icon next to White's name.
            
        The 12* protocol and the pie rule cannot be combined in this implementation, but komi is compatible with either choice.")
        (id "1936")
        (version "1.3.1")
        (classification "")
        (author "Michael Amundsen and Luis Bolanos Mures")
        (credit "Michael Amundsen")
